<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-05-02T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-05-02T15:00:00-05:00" n="444" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d444">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/4320: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-05-02T16:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">May 2, 1922—4
                                        p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>108. Your telegram, May 1, 11 p.m., no. 187. If Colonel Martin and
                            Admiral Strauss approve, the Department does not object to <pb facs="0818" n="698" xml:id="pg_698"/> the substitution of marines
                            for soldiers called for in your telegram of April 29, 3 p.m., no.
                            177.</p>
                        <p>Report any developments of importance, especially any increase by other
                            foreign powers of their military forces and any evidence indicating
                            anti-foreign tendency.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>